  "prompt": "How do I unlock my laptop keyboard?",
  "response": "The method for unlocking your laptop keyboard depends on why it's locked. Here are the most common reasons and how to troubleshoot each:\n\n**1. Accidental Key Combination Lock (Most Common):**\n\n*   **Check for the Fn Lock (Function Lock) Key:**\n    *   Look for a key on your keyboard labeled \"Fn Lock,\" \"F Lock,\" or similar (often with a padlock icon). It's usually in the top row (F1-F12) or near the Esc key.\n    *   **To Unlock:** Press the **Fn key + the Fn Lock key** *simultaneously*.  On some laptops, it might be just pressing the Fn Lock key directly. Watch for an on-screen notification or a light turning on/off indicating Fn Lock is engaged/disengaged.\n    *   **Why this works:** Some keyboards have a feature to toggle the Fn keys between their standard function (F1, F2, etc.) and their special function (volume, brightness, etc.). Accidental pressing of Fn Lock can leave the special functions permanently engaged, making the primary keys not work as expected.\n\n**2. Sticky Keys or Filter Keys Enabled:**\n\n*   **Sticky Keys:** This feature makes modifier keys (Shift, Ctrl, Alt) \"stick\" so you don't have to hold them down while pressing another key.\n*   **Filter Keys:** This feature ignores brief or repeated keystrokes, which can make typing difficult if enabled accidentally.\n*   **How to Check and Disable:**\n    *   **Windows:**\n        1.  Press the **Shift key 5 times rapidly**. This often triggers the Sticky Keys prompt.\n        2.  If the Sticky Keys prompt appears, click \"No\" (or choose the option to disable Sticky Keys).\n        3.  **To permanently disable:** Type \"Control Panel\" in the Windows search bar and open Control Panel.\n        4.  Go to \"Ease of Access\" or \"Accessibility\" (depending on your Windows version).\n        5.  Click on \"Change how your keyboard works\" or \"Keyboard settings.\"\n        6.  Uncheck the boxes for \"Turn on Sticky Keys\" and \"Turn on Filter Keys.\"\n        7.  Click \"Apply\" and \"OK.\"\n    *   **macOS:**\n        1.  Go to **System Preferences** (Apple menu > System Preferences).\n        2.  Click on **Accessibility**.\n        3.  In the left sidebar, select **Keyboard**.\n        4.  Click on **Hardware**.\n        5.  Uncheck the box for \"Sticky Keys\" and \"Slow Keys.\"\n\n**3. Num Lock Enabled (If Only Numbers Are Affected):**\n\n*   **Check the Num Lock Key:** Look for a key labeled \"Num Lock\" or \"Num Lk.\"  It's usually on the numeric keypad area of the keyboard.\n*   **To Unlock:** Press the Num Lock key.  An indicator light (if present) will turn off, indicating Num Lock is disabled.  This will allow the number keys on the numeric keypad to function as arrow keys, Home, End, PgUp, PgDn, etc.\n\n**4. Driver Issues:**\n\n*   **Driver Corruption or Outdated Drivers:** Sometimes, the keyboard driver can become corrupted or outdated, causing the keyboard to malfunction.\n*   **How to Update or Reinstall Drivers (Windows):**\n    1.  Right-click on the **Start button** and select **Device Manager**.\n    2.  Expand the \"Keyboards\" category.\n    3.  Right-click on your keyboard (usually listed as \"Standard PS/2 Keyboard\" or a similar name).\n    4.  Select **\"Update driver\"**.  Choose \"Search automatically for drivers.\"  Windows will try to find and install the latest driver.\n    5.  If updating doesn't work, try **\"Uninstall device\"**. Then, restart your laptop. Windows will usually automatically reinstall the driver upon restart.\n*   **Driver Issues (macOS):**  macOS generally handles drivers automatically.  However, it's a good idea to make sure your operating system is up to date:  **Apple menu > System Preferences > Software Update**.\n\n**5. Hardware Problem:**\n\n*   **Physical Damage or Loose Connection:** If none of the above solutions work, there might be a hardware problem with the keyboard itself.  This is more likely if you've recently spilled something on the keyboard or dropped the laptop.\n*   **Troubleshooting Hardware:**\n    *   **External Keyboard:** Try connecting an external USB keyboard to your laptop. If the external keyboard works, it strongly suggests a problem with the internal keyboard.\n    *   **Clean the Keyboard:** Use compressed air to blow out any dust or debris that might be lodged under the keys.\n    *   **Check for Loose Connections (Advanced - Requires Disassembly):**  If you're comfortable with it, you *can* try opening your laptop and checking the keyboard's ribbon cable connection to the motherboard. *However, this can void your warranty, so proceed with extreme caution or seek professional help.*\n    *   **Professional Repair:** If the external keyboard works and you suspect a hardware problem with the internal keyboard, the best course of action is to take your laptop to a qualified repair technician.\n\n**6. System Issues/Temporary Glitch:**\n\n*   **Restart Your Laptop:** A simple restart can often resolve temporary glitches that might be causing the keyboard to malfunction.\n\n**Specific Scenarios and Tips:**\n\n*   **Only some keys are not working:** This suggests either a hardware problem with those specific keys or a localized software issue. Try cleaning the keyboard thoroughly.  If the affected keys are next to each other, it could indicate a spill.\n*   **The keyboard worked fine and then suddenly stopped:** Try a system restore to a point before the problem started (Windows).\n*   **Recently installed software/updates:** Try uninstalling the software or reverting to a previous version of the driver.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Back up your data:** Before attempting any major troubleshooting steps (especially driver updates or system restores), it's always a good idea to back up your important data.\n*   **Consult your laptop's manual:** Your laptop's manual may have specific troubleshooting steps or keyboard shortcuts related to keyboard locking/unlocking.\n*   **Search online for your specific laptop model:** Searching online for \"keyboard not working [your laptop model]\" can often yield specific solutions or known issues related to your particular laptop.\n\nBy systematically working through these troubleshooting steps, you should be able to identify and resolve the issue preventing your laptop keyboard from working.  Good luck!\n",
